{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01P12WWF9tNGfLsHMtJpTnDh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a complete picture. The `log4j2.file.properties` is the file-based version of the logging configuration, and I need to use it as the ES log4j2 configuration so that ES writes logs to files.\n\nLooking at the file-based config:\n- Server logs: `${sys:es.logs.base_path}/${sys:es.logs.cluster_name}_server.json`\n- Old-style pattern: `${sys:es.logs.base_path}/${sys:es.logs.cluster_name}.log`\n- etc.\n- The base path defaults to `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs`\n\nSo my approach is to create three ConfigMaps—one for the log4j2 configuration, one for Metricbeat, and one for Filebeat—then patch the StatefulSet to mount an emptyDir volume at the logs directory so Elasticsearch can write to it.\n\nI need to be careful with the StatefulSet patch since there are already init containers handling plugins and keystore setup, plus existing volume mounts for the config file and data PVC. I'll need to add the new volumes and sidecar containers without disrupting that existing setup.\n\nNow I'm planning out the metricbeat and filebeat sidecars — metricbeat will monitor the local Elasticsearch instance and ship metrics to the monitoring cluster, while filebeat will collect logs from the ES container.\n\nI need to think through the volume mounting strategy carefully. The ES container writes logs to `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs` based on the log4j2 configuration, and if I mount an emptyDir there, it will overlay that directory. The GC logs are handled separately by JVM flags, so they should still write to the mounted volume alongside the application logs.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6540,"cache_read_input_tokens":45511,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6540},"