{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015tWaN79EJAdinFaRwvDs5W","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I need to restart Filebeat in all pods to pick up the new ConfigMap. Since Filebeat is a sidecar in a StatefulSet pod, I can restart just the Filebeat container using `kubectl rollout restart`. But wait - a StatefulSet rollout restart will restart all pods in order. That's fine since I want the new ConfigMap to be picked up.\n\nActually, since ConfigMaps are mounted as volumes in Kubernetes (using subPath mounts), the file won't be automatically updated when the ConfigMap changes. For a subPath mount, the file is NOT automatically refreshed when the ConfigMap is updated. \n\nThe issue is that Kubernetes doesn't let me restart individual containers within a pod - I have to restart the whole pod. A rolling restart of the StatefulSet would work, but it's disruptive since it restarts Elasticsearch too. Let me think about whether there's a less invasive approach here.\n\nActually, before I commit to restarting everything, let me check if the monitoring indices are already showing up in the monitoring cluster from the Metricbeat data that's been flowing in. If they are, then the core objective is already met and the Filebeat restart becomes less critical.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":713,"cache_read_input_tokens":77144,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":713},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"77ff193e-e364-4989-988e-248143808fa8","uuid":"704e1f2a-0ab6-413d-8b64-e23a4c9a68fd","request_id":"req_011CcfyuNuCUDfutvovS2JQH"}
