{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01EZHbKxxgfCfhQ3G48H94wQ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Everything is working as expected:\n\n1. **Every ES pod has 3 containers**: `elasticsearch,metricbeat,filebeat` - all 3 showing `true,true,true` (all ready) ✓\n\n2. **Monitoring indices in the monitoring cluster**:\n   - `.monitoring-es-7-mb-2026.07.03` - Metricbeat monitoring data (11 docs) ✓\n   - `monitoring-es-logs-2026.07.03` - Filebeat log data (7465 docs) ✓\n   - `metricbeat-7.17.9-2026.07.03-000001` - Additional metricbeat data (278 docs) ✓\n\n3. **ES cluster health**: Green, 3 nodes ✓\n\nThe `metricbeat-7.17.9-*` index gets created because Metricbeat's own `output.elasticsearch` generates self-monitoring data, while `.monitoring-es-7-mb-*` is the proper stack monitoring index from `xpack.enabled: true`. I'm noticing the `.monitoring-es-7-mb-2026.07.03` doc count is still at 11, so let me investigate why it's not increasing.\n\nThe `metricbeat-7.17.9-*` indices are clearly growing (94 → 189 → 278 docs, with each pod adding roughly 94 docs per cycle), so data is flowing. But the `.monitoring-es-7-mb-*` index staying at 11 is odd—those docs are from the old pods before the restart, and the new pods haven't contributed yet. I'm wondering if there's an issue with how the xpack.enabled path is working, or if the new pods just haven't sent their first batch of monitoring data. Looking at Metricbeat's behavior, when `xpack.enabled: true` in the elasticsearch module, it should ship to `.monitoring-es-7-mb-*`, but the `output.elasticsearch` also creates the `metricbeat-7.17.9-*` indices as a separate output.\n\nActually, I think I've got it backwards—with `xpack.enabled: true`, the data goes directly to `.monitoring-es-7-mb-*` and the regular output shouldn't be used for that module data. So why is `metricbeat-7.17.9-*` growing at all? That index should only exist if Metricbeat is sending data through the regular output path without xpack. Looking at the monitoring output logs, I can see the libbeat and metricbeat metrics being reported, which suggests the monitoring.enabled metrics are going to the regular output instead. I'm realizing the confusion here—when `xpack.enabled: true` is set in the elasticsearch module, Metricbeat formats the collected metrics as monitoring data and sends them to the output, which then writes them to `.monitoring-es-7-mb-*` indices. But separately, Metricbeat also has its own internal beats_stats and beats_state data that flows through the default pipeline, which is why `metricbeat-7.17.9-*` indices are being created even though I expected them to be suppressed. Looking at the event counts from the metricsets, I'm seeing 6 events total from the elasticsearch module outputs but 7 events were acked, so there's an extra event coming from somewhere. I'm wondering if the `metricbeat-7.17.9-*` index might be getting data from Metricbeat's internal monitoring or possibly from an `enrich` metricset.\n\nActually, I should stop overthinking this. The important thing is that the monitoring infrastructure is working: the `.monitoring-es-7-mb-*` index exists with proper metrics, the logs index is growing steadily at 7465 docs, all three pods have their containers running, and the cluster is green. The doc count in the monitoring index is still at 11 from before the restart, which is a bit odd. Let me give it more time to see if it increases now that the fresh Metricbeat instances started at 23:27.\n\nWith each pod running for about 4 minutes and a 10-second collection period, I'd expect around 72 total collections across all three pods, accounting for some startup failures. But the monitoring index still shows only 11 docs, which suggests something might be off with how the xpack monitoring data is being written. Let me investigate what these 11 docs actually contain.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":